=== Ch2_Scope_Intro ===
Chapter 2: Which services, and what about AI? # diagram: which_services.jpg

Questions 29-33 ask which apps and services should be restricted. Questions 34-38 tackle AI chatbots.

*   [Which services questions.]
    -> Ch2_Q29
*   [AI chatbot questions.]
    -> Ch2_Q34

=== Ch2_Q29 ===
Questions 29-33 ask:

"What factors are important when determining which apps, sites or services to apply minimum age restrictions to?"

And: "Are there types of apps or services you'd want captured by age restrictions?"

And: "Are there types you'd want exempted?"

*   [What should I watch for?]
    -> Ch2_Q29_Analysis

=== Ch2_Q29_Analysis ===
These questions determine the scope of everything discussed so far. Whether the restrictions apply to ten platforms or ten thousand depends on what gets defined as "in scope."

The consultation mentions "services with user-to-user interaction" as a possible criterion. That includes:
• Social media (Instagram, TikTok, Snapchat)
• Messaging apps (WhatsApp, Discord, Telegram)
• Gaming platforms (Roblox, Fortnite, Minecraft, Steam)
• Educational platforms with chat features
• Forums, fan communities, support groups

Some services are already exempt from the Online Safety Act—internal business services, educational services, services with limited functionality. Q33 asks if more exemptions are needed.

The danger is in the default: everything is in scope unless explicitly exempted. If your child uses an online platform with any social features—and most do—it could require age verification.

*   [Tell me about gaming specifically.]
    -> Ch2_Gaming_Scope
*   [Move to AI chatbots.]
    -> Ch2_Q34

=== Ch2_Gaming_Scope ===
This is where the consultation's framing gets sneaky.

The 76-page consultation document discusses gaming extensively. It mentions Roblox, online gaming communities, and gaming as a significant part of children's online lives.

But the actual survey questions never say "gaming." They say "online services" and "functionalities."

Most parents thinking about "social media restrictions" are imagining Instagram and TikTok. They're not thinking about Minecraft servers, Roblox, or Fortnite—platforms where their children play with friends.

If someone asks your child to prove their identity before they can play games online with their schoolmates, how would you feel? That question isn't in the consultation. But it's the logical outcome.

If this concerns you, Q30 and Q32 are the free-text boxes where you can flag it.

*   [Now tell me about AI.]
    -> Ch2_Q34
*   [Skip ahead.]
    -> Overview_Chapters

=== Ch2_Q34 ===
Questions 34-38 ask about AI chatbots.

"What are the benefits to children of using AI chatbots?"
"Which features are most risky?"
"Should AI chatbots have minimum age restrictions?"

*   [What's different about the AI section?]
    -> Ch2_Q34_Analysis

=== Ch2_Q34_Analysis ===
This section is more genuinely exploratory than the social media questions. The government doesn't have a fixed policy on AI yet—these questions are actually trying to figure out what to do.

But there are still concerns with the framing.

The consultation treats AI chatbots as a category alongside social media—but they're fundamentally different. An AI chatbot is a tool. Social media is a network. The risks are different: hallucination and emotional dependency versus peer pressure and content exposure.

Yet the consultation applies the same age-restriction framework to both, as if the same solution fits.

*   [What's the bigger concern?]
    -> Ch2_AI_Concern

=== Ch2_AI_Concern ===
By including AI in a consultation framed around "protecting children," they're establishing a precedent: AI regulation equals child safety.

That framing could be used to justify much broader AI restrictions later—restrictions that have nothing to do with children but inherit the political cover of child protection.

Also note: AI tutoring tools like Khan Academy's Khanmigo could be caught by blanket age restrictions on "AI chatbots." The line between "AI chatbot" and "educational tool with AI" and "search engine with AI features" is blurry—and the consultation doesn't draw it.

If you use AI tools for education, creativity, or learning—say so in Q34. If you think blanket restrictions would harm beneficial uses—say so in Q38.

